repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
version_unique_justification: For now, the project is public but unreleased, hence all commits so far are not "intended to be used by users". As soon as the library is released, semantic version numbers will be attached to releases and the appropriate commits will be tagged accordingly.
report_tracker_justification: Issues can be raised via the GitHub issue tracking system: https://github.com/JanHett/spice/issues
report_process_justification: Issues can be raised via the GitHub issue tracking system: https://github.com/JanHett/spice/issues
report_archive_justification: The project uses the GitHub issue tracking system: https://github.com/JanHett/spice/issues
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: Vulnerabilities are reported the same way issues are: https://github.com/JanHett/spice/tree/clean-build-system#contributing
tests_are_added_justification: Tests are generally added in the same commit or commits as the feature.
warnings_justification: All warnings as well as -Werror are enabled
know_secure_design_justification:
While I am by no means a security expert, I consider my experience (acquired designing an API serving ~10k clients as well as in a university course on low level development) sufficient for the purpose of addressing the basic security design choices of an image processing library.
That being said, spice is a learning project. I do my best to keep it secure enough for its intended purpose, but I can't pretend that I'm perfect ;-).
know_common_errors_justification:
spice itself avoids security related functionality. Nevertheless, certain parts of spice might be used to introduce vulnerabilities into the library's users' code (specifically via buffer overflow/unchecked memory access). This is by design and unfortunately necessary to meet the speed requirements of image processing tasks.
That being said, spice is a learning project. I do my best to keep it secure enough for its intended purpose, but I can't pretend that I'm perfect ;-).
static_analysis_justification:
https://app.codacy.com/manual/JanHett/spice/dashboard
Clang tidy, cppcheck etc. are planned but not yet implemented
dynamic_analysis_justification: ASAN is included in Debug build
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.

name: butler-graphql
description: An opinionated GraphQL package for Laravel.
contribution_justification: Projects on GitHub by default use issues and pull requests, as encouraged by documentation such as <https://guides.github.com/activities/contributing-to-open-source/>.
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/blob/master/LICENSE>.
floss_license_justification: The MIT license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The MIT license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: The README.md file has basic information about interacting with the library:<https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/blob/master/README.md#getting-started>.
documentation_interface_justification: The README.md file has basic information about interacting with the library:<https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/blob/master/README.md#getting-started>.
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
release_notes_justification: Non-trivial release notes file in repository: <https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md>.
report_tracker_justification: Uses the github provided issue tracker: https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aopen+sort%3Aupdated-desc
report_responses_justification: One issue reported during the last 12 months. https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/issues?q=is%3Aissue+sort%3Aupdated-desc+is%3Aclosed
enhancement_responses_justification: One issue reported during the last 12 months, feature added. https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/issues/10
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: No "private" reports are in scope at this moment.
build_justification: The library is written in PHP and is supposed to be interpreted. How consuming applications actually behave is hard to tell.
build_common_tools_justification: Generally not a library used in an environment that is process in a build system.
build_floss_tools_justification: Generally not a library used in an environment that is process in a build system. Code can be written in any tool. Is supposed to be consumed via PHP and that is in itself FLOSS.
test_invocation_justification:
execute `composer install` followed by `phpunit` in the root directory of the project.
https://getcomposer.org/doc/00-intro.md#using-composer
https://phpunit.readthedocs.io/en/9.3/textui.html
test_most_justification: All but one else statement is covered in the current test suite.
test_policy_justification: Tests are supposed to be included with a code change,
tests_are_added_justification: All commits not touching the tests directory can be classified as either a release commit or a documentation change. Documentation changes includes dependecy chains for external components. See the git history to dispute this claim.
tests_documented_added_justification: The need for unit tests are covered by the contribution section of the README. https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/#how-to-contribute
warnings_justification: Uses linter tool phpcs to conform to a coherent code standard but no compiler flags are needed strictly speaking.
warnings_fixed_justification: In general linter warnings are not acceptable, they can be ignored with line rules if needed be but that has not been the case yet.
warnings_strict_justification: PHP has no real strict mode like that.
delivery_mitm_justification: Sources are provided out of github servers and they are available over https (and ssh for committers).
static_analysis_justification:
phpcs is executed by a GitHub Action during pull requests and pushes. https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/actions
Static analysis is performed by Scrutinizer . https://scrutinizer-ci.com/g/glesys/butler-graphql/
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: Static analysis is performed by Scrutinizer . https://scrutinizer-ci.com/g/glesys/butler-graphql/
static_analysis_often_justification: Both GitHub Actions and Scrutinizer are triggered by hooks.
dynamic_analysis_justification: A complete testsuite is executed on pull requests.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: Project is not written in a memory-unsafe language.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: The software does check for potential error conditions and either handles them silently (when appropriate) or throws exceptions.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio:
Using GitHub Actions to automatically execute the test suite on all new commits. Result is displayed upfront at the GitHub rendering of the README.md file.
https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/actions
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
english_justification: The README.md is in English and the issue tracker at github is open and assumed to be used, the core development team is fluent in Swedish and English and assumes that the communication will be in English first.
hardened_site_justification:
Using GitHub for everything regarding the code.
https://securityheaders.com/?q=https%3A%2F%2Fgithub.com%2Fglesys%2Fbutler-graphql&followRedirects=on
build_reproducible_justification: Written and consumed in PHP, a interpreted language.
access_continuity_justification:
The development is hosted by GleSYS AB.
https://github.com/glesys/
https://glesys.com/developers
documentation_current_justification:
The README holds examples on how to consume the library and how to use the deeper features it offers.
https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/blob/master/README.md#digging-deeper
accessibility_best_practices_justificati: This is a library not meant for end user consumption.
internationalization_justification: This is a library not meant for end user consumption.
maintenance_or_update_justification: The code is handled in semver fashion with release notes describing the changes. https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/releases
vulnerability_response_process_justifica:
Uses the github provided issue tracker: https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aopen+sort%3Aupdated-desc
This is described in the contribution section of the README.
coding_standards_justification: The Laravel project style guide are the choice. https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/blob/master/README.md#code-standard
coding_standards_enforced_justification: phpcs is executed by Travis and Scrutinizer. Coding standards are documented to be following PSR-2 and PSR-4.
build_standard_variables_justification: This is a interpreted project, no binaries are built.
build_preserve_debug_justification: This is a interpreted project, no binaries are built.
build_non_recursive_justification: This is a interpreted project, no binaries are built.
build_repeatable_justification: This is a interpreted project, no binaries are built.
installation_standard_variables_justific: This is a PHP library used inside other Laravel based PHP applications.
installation_development_quick_justifica: This is a PHP library used inside other Laravel based PHP applications.
external_dependencies_justification:
Uses PHP Composer to sort out dependencies.
https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/blob/master/composer.json
dependency_monitoring_justification:
Using the GitHub dependabot mechanism to weekly check external dependencies and suggest updates when there are new versions made available.
Logs are available at https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/network/updates
updateable_reused_components_justificati: Uses PHP Composer to sort out dependencies.
interfaces_current_justification: There are no proprietary dependencies to use this library in any way.
automated_integration_testing_justificat: Travis builds all commits on pull requests and pushes. https://travis-ci.org/glesys/butler-graphql
regression_tests_added50_justification: No bugs reported yet. Policy is to cover all code with tests, using regression test specifically is common among the core developers.
test_statement_coverage80_justification:
The phpunit test suite covers 100% of original code and most of the boiler plated Laravel code.
Scrutinizer holds coverage information. https://scrutinizer-ci.com/g/glesys/butler-graphql/code-structure/master/code-coverage
test_policy_mandated_justification: All code contributions need to have tests to be accepted. Exceptions can be made after public discussion, see the contribution guide: https://github.com/glesys/butler-graphql/#how-to-contribute
input_validation_justification: The input validation provided by Laravel is used for everything passed from outside the library. In contact with databases a ORM layer is used.
two_person_review_justification: It's a core internal practice to do a more than one person review of all code. It's not documented in code but in the historic PRs available at the project page.
test_statement_coverage90_justification:
PHPUnit can produce coverage reports for the project. 
https://phpunit.readthedocs.io/en/9.3/code-coverage-analysis.html
test_branch_coverage80_justification:
PHPUnit can produce coverage reports for the project. 
https://phpunit.readthedocs.io/en/9.3/code-coverage-analysis.html
